body:
Under certain environment, PSVersion of 5.0.10586.117, Write-Host redirected with *>>1 writes `InformationRecord` structure representation of the message into a file instead of a message itself.

The bug does not show up under lower versions (no in 4.0, 3.0).

When I run the script manually it works fine. It reproduces only when Consul executes it with Win32 API. I did not investigate further environment differences.
## Steps to reproduce

We use pretty complicated setup. I don't know how to reproduce it.
- We have Consul running run.bat as healthcheck
- run.bat runs powershell sessions with run.ps1
- run.ps1 run external scripts redirecting all logs to a file append

Run.bat have:

``` batch
:: run.bat

@ECHO OFF
PowerShell.exe -NoProfile -NonInteractive -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Command "& %~dpn0.ps1" %*
EXIT /B %errorlevel%
```

Run.ps1 partly looks like:

``` powershell
function Run($WrappedCmd, $BoundParameters, $LogFile, $InputObject) {
        $runspacepool = [runspacefactory]::CreateRunspacePool(1, 1, $SessionState, $Host)
        $runspacepool.Open()  

        # $executor will be taken by parent context closure
        $ps = [powershell]::Create().AddScript('
            param($WrappedCmd, $BoundParameters, $LogFile, $InputObject)

            $Response = 0
            # Catch Response via Closure boundaries (ignoring full redirect of pipe)
            function Foo {
                Param(
                    [parameter(ValueFromPipeline)]
                    $InputObject)

                Begin {}
                Process { 
                    Set-Variable -Name "Response" -Value $_ -Scope 1; $_ 
                }
                End {}
            }

            try {
                $Executor = {
                    try {
                        Write-Host "Hi"                 
                    } catch {
                        Write-Error-Detailed -E $_
                        throw $_
                    }
                }

                if ($LogFile) {
                    # <output> stream redirected as well. thus, it will handle only exceptions
                    # auto converting them to Error Code (2).
                    (& $Executor | Foo) *>> $LogFile
                    return $Response
                } else {
                    & $Executor
                }
            } catch {   
                # $_ was pushed on top of $error, printed by $Executor
                return $_
            } finally {}
            ').AddArgument($WrappedCmd).AddArgument($BoundParameters).AddArgument($LogFile)

        if ($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey("InputObject")) {
            $ps = $ps.AddArgument($InputObject)
        }

        $ps.RunspacePool = $runspacepool

        try {        
            $async = $ps.BeginInvoke()            
            $async.AsyncWaitHandle.WaitOne($ScriptTimeout, $false) | Out-Null
            if (-not $async.IsCompleted) {            
                $ps.Stop()

                Write-Host "Script run out of time..."
                if ($LogFile) {
                    Write-Output "Script run out of time..." *>> $LogFile
                }                

                Write-Output $TimeoutErrorCode
            } else {
                Write-Output $ps.EndInvoke($async)
            }
        } catch {
            Write-Output 2
        } finally {
            $ps.Dispose()
            $runspacepool.Close()
        }    
    }
```

this run in complicated setup of pipelined function, which in its turn used as `$inpud | run thing`
## Expected behavior

```
$ cat FILE
```

must contain

```
Hi
```
## Actual behavior

Result file contains

```
